<DOC><DOCNO> AP890420-0185 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 2113EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Madagascar-Riots     04-20 0242</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Madagascar-Riots,0249</SECOND><HEAD>Three Deaths Reported In Clashes Between Opposition, Authorities</HEAD><DATELINE>ANTANANARIVO, Madagascar (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Demonstrators protesting whatthey call the fraudulent re-election of President Didier Ratsirakafought with police in clashes that left three people dead and about60 injured, news reports said.   The French news agency Agence France-Presse said the violencebroke out Wednesday afternoon after a rally called by an oppositioncoalition.   It said several hundred demonstrators, mostly young, burnedvehicles and looted stores in the center of Antananarivo, thecapital of the Indian Ocean island nation. The agency quotedinformed sources as saying young children were among the injured.It said authorities gave no indication how many people werearrested.   The report cited what it called a provisional official count ofthe casualties. The count could not immediately be confirmed.   In a previous round of clashes following an opposition rallySunday, the government-controlled radio said 13 people were hurt,including three policemen, and 20 people were arrested.   Ratsiraka, chosen by the military to rule in 1975, wasre-elected to a third seven-year term on March 12 with about 62percent of the vote. The three opposition parties challenged theoutcome in the island nation's Supreme Court, saying the voting wasrigged.   The opposition leaders are proposing formation of a provisionalgovernment, including representatives of the military, students andchurches, to rule while new elections are prepared.   Ceremonies marking the beginning of Ratsiraka's third term werescheduled later Thursday.</TEXT></DOC>